        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Sensitivity:  We request a 1sigma sensitivity of 1 mJy/bm in a 10 km/s channel. This requirement is based in part on our ALMA Cycle 1 observations of HCN 4-3, CS 7-6, and continuum observations at 0.5" resolution (2011.0.00.175 PI:Scoville, Swarnima, Sheth et al).   HCN emission is essentially unresolved in the EW direction and shows a velocity gradient along the NS bridge connecting the two nuclei (see Figure 1).  HCN 4-3 emission ranges from 15 to 30 mJy/bm.   The worst case scenario is that the HCN emission is uniform within the ALMA cycle 1  0.5" beam; the flux would then be about 11 times weaker in our 0.15" beam, or about 1.4 sigma in each beam if our CO and HCO+ emission had the same brightness as HCN.   However:  (1) emission is very unlikely to be uniformly distributed; and (2) CO is almost always observed to be far brighter than HCN; models by Meijerink, Spaans, &amp; Israel 2007 predict CO 3-2 will be 3 to 100 times brighter, depending on conditions.   HCO+ 4-3 (our secondary line) is predicted to be 50% weaker than HCN 4-3 in low-CR PDRs but as much as an order of magnitude brighter in the XDR regions near black holes.  JCMT observations of NGC 6240 in a 13" beam by Greve et al 2009 show CO 3-2 ~20 times brighter than HCN 4-3.  The JCMT observations also show HCN 4-3 somewhat stronger than HCO+ 4-3 and CS 7-6, whereas the ALMA data show HCN enhanced relative to CS close to the nucleus.  Based on the models, we would expect similar or greater enhancement for HCO+.   One ALMA configuration will suffice to cover structures on arc-second and smaller size scales, the relevant size scales for understanding the circumnuclear disk.

Imaging: The two nuclei are separated by 1.5" and the region of interest is smaller than 1/3 of the 18" ALMA primary beam, and a single pointing suffices.  Note also that ScienceGoal 2 is a 7-field mosaic of the same source at 0.4" resolution and so will give good uv coverage to lower brightness, more extended emission.

Correlator Setup: The primary line is the CO 3-2 line, with a velocity range less than 1000 km/s and with +/- 500 km/s, easily included with the 1875 MHz bandwidth.     The hanning smoothed resolution is ~1 kms km/s but we would likely we
smooth to 10km/s as this would be appropriate for discriminating between simulations and scenarios.  Our main  science goal is to get 10km/s channels for which this choice of the spw is adequate.    HCO+ would be observed with a similar setup.     Due to the location of the CS 7-6 line, it is not possible to get 1875 MHz bandwidth centered on the line, so the CS is at one extreme and the other part of the 1875 MHz window will be used for continuum.   The fourth correlator window covers continuum.

Calibration:  System defined is chosen - nothing special needed.

Bandpass Accuracy - There is no special need for additional bandpass accuracy.

Schedule / Time constraints: None

Data Rate:  Safely within limits.

Special constraints:  None
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
