        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: 

Our primary goal is the gas dynamics and morphology (eg tidal filaments etc) of the molecular gas in the disrupted disks of the merging galaxies.  The 3-2 CO line is ideal because emission is strong in PDRs, XDRs, and shocks.  From JCMT observations, we have the flux integrated in the 13" beam, ~3000 Jy km/s.   Taking the line width of ~400 km/s, this implies a mean flux of 7.5 Jy in the 13" beam.   The worst case scenario is that the flux is uniformly distributed, in which case the flux in a 0.4" beam will be 7 mJy.   With a sensitivity of 0.002 mJy, this gives S/N of 3.5.   In principle, we might relax the sensitivity requirement somewhat, but then the bulk of the time would be lost to overhead and calibration; furthermore, our experience is that good S/N is essential for detecting distributed flux with an interferometer.   

Imaging:   The CO 1-0 PdBI maps of Feruglio et al 2012 indicate a maximum extent &lt; 10" in any velocity channel and a region of interest of about 20".   Thus we choose a 7-point Nyquist sampled mosaic to cover a 20" rectangle.

Correlator Setup: The primary line is the CO 3-2 line, with a velocity range with wings that extend over nearly 1400 km/s; thus the 1875 MHz bandwidth (1660 km/s) is adequate.     The hanning smoothed resolution is ~1 kms km/s but we would likely we
smooth to 10km/s as this would be appropriate for discriminating between simulations and scenarios.  Our main  science goal is to get 10km/s channels for which this choice of the spw is adequate.    HCO+ would be observed with a similar setup.     Due to the location of the CS 7-6 line, it is not possible to get 1875 MHz bandwidth centered on the line, so the CS is at one extreme and the other part of the 1875 MHz window will be used for continuum.   The fourth correlator window covers continuum.

Calibration:  System defined is chosen - nothing special needed.

Bandpass Accuracy - There is no special need for additional bandpass accuracy.

